@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Demo";
    var extension = new DemoExtension();
}

<div class="text-center">
    <h1 class="display-4">Welcome to CoreXF</h1>
</div>
<p>This is a demo of CoreXF (.NET Core eXtensibility Framework). This demo references <code>CoreXF.Abstractions</code> and exposes its functionality through the <code>DemoExtension</code> class.</p>
<h5>Basic description of the demo:</h5>
<ul>
    <li>There are two controllers: <code>HomeController</code> and <code>DemoController</code>. In order to avoid name clashes <code>HomeController</code> is decorated with <code>CoreXFIgnore</code> attribute. This effectively "cloaks" it from host app.</li>
    <li>The DemoMvc app can be run as usual (it is a "normal" ASP.NET Core app). It can be "deployed" to the Extensions folder in the host app and run as an extension.</li>
    <li>The Post-Build events help in deploying the extension to its host app (HostApp), take a look: right-click on the project -> Properties -> Build -> Events -> Post-Build Events. (Or you can just copy the output dir to an Extensions sub-folder, usually named after extension name.)</li>
</ul>

<h5>Here are the extension properties:</h5>
